Yes/No/Maybe — does airway surgery lower serum lipid levels in obstructive sleep apnea patients?
Answer: \boxed{}
Based on the retrieved evidence, there is no direct indication that airway surgery specifically lowers serum lipid levels in obstructive sleep apnea patients. While some studies mention improvements in hyperlipidemia post-weight-loss surgery, these benefits are primarily linked to substantial weight reduction rather than the surgical correction of airway anatomy per se. Thus, any lipid reductions observed are attributable to concomitant weight loss, not the airway surgery itself.
\boxed{\text{B}}

